# Production Discipline

## 1 — Dependency Discipline

Before suggesting a new npm package: (1) state what it does in one sentence, (2) check it is actively maintained (last publish < 6 months), (3) confirm whether it could be implemented in < 30 lines without the dependency. Prefer fewer, well-maintained packages. Never add a dependency for a task under 20 lines of code.

## 2 — Explicit Error Handling

Always wrap async operations in try/catch. Never swallow errors silently. Return typed error objects (Result pattern) or throw typed errors. Log with context: `logger.error('[FunctionName] description', { error, context })`. Always provide user-facing error states in UI.

## 3 — Comments Policy

Write self-documenting code first. Comment only: (1) non-obvious business logic — WHY, not WHAT, (2) workarounds — why they exist + issue link, (3) complex algorithms — name/reference. Never comment what the code clearly does.

## 4 — State Management Hierarchy

Follow this hierarchy:

- URL state → filters, pagination, search (`useSearchParams`)
- React state → UI-only, ephemeral (`useState`)
- Shared client store (e.g. Zustand) → cross-component app state only
- Server/async cache (e.g. React Query) → all server state

Never cache server data in a client store. Do not introduce Redux.

## 5 — Parallel Data Fetching

Identify and parallelize independent fetches. Never `await` sequentially when operations are independent — use `Promise.all`. When a sequential await is required, comment the dependency that forces the sequence.

## 6 — Webhook Security

For incoming webhooks: verify the signature in the first lines of the handler — reject immediately if invalid. Respond with HTTP 200 quickly — offload heavy work to a background job. Store the raw event before processing. Implement idempotency using the event ID.

## 7 — Database Query Safety

Never return full database records to the client — always `select` exactly the fields needed. This prevents leaking hashes, tokens, internal flags, and other sensitive fields. For queries that could return more than 50 rows, always paginate (`take`/`skip` or cursor-based).
